                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/882.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-17T18:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 17, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In the interview with the Minister for Foreign Affairs he asked if the note
                    delivered to him, which he inferred from my manner was serious, was the same
                    referred to by the President in his interview with Mr. Calero on September 4. I
                    replied that it was. He then asked me if this Government could depend upon me to
                    make <pb facs="0963" n="847" xml:id="pg_847"/> representations to Washington of
                    a sympathetic and helpful character. I replied that the character of my office
                    placed upon me the obligation of always [laboring?] in the interest of amicable
                    feeling between Mexico and the United States, but that he must understand that
                    in order for me to be helpful his Government must show a disposition to do
                    justice to mine and actively bestir itself in the matters treated of in the
                    note. He said that he would formally acknowledge the note at once and make
                    adequate reply in four or five days.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
